I had expected "AI" - or what this phenomenon also is called - to be a quick learner, but after a year it still struggles with the problems that traditionally have been a pain - hair and parts of a subject that has less contrast to the background and demand real human pattern recognition. To me it seems that AI is just a pattern analyzing tool that selects a refining mode from a database and goes wrong eight out of ten times, still leaving all the brain work to his master when it comes to the critical details. It would probably work better, if AI identified matching hair patterns from a db and replaced the subject with those matches. That would not be 100 percent true to the original, but it would look that way, provided you didn't have the original to compare with - which is the typical situation for most end users. I think the best AI sharpening tools work that way already.

You need to finesse things a little, but it's great for real estate videos.

The stock photography game has flipped in the last 20 years.  I was (well still am) with Getty.  Back in the early 2000s the money I received thru my royalties paid all my expenses.  One shoot I did for Getty--one day production set on a train in a train yard in LA with a hipster couple, business men, older traveling couple--made me probably $35K (after Getty's commission) and this was with Getty paying for all of the production.  They offered to let me pay for the production and my royalty percentage would have doubled but I didn't want to spend $25K on the cost of production--train rental, model fees, wardrobe stylist fees/expenses, equipment rental, etc.  I calculated that over the year or two the shoot remained relevant I would have made $80k for that one day shoot which is insane.  I'd average around 6-10K a month.  Now with the digital letting more and more people jump into photography it is a challenge to see any substantial income from stock.  And yes, your images will be up on the stock site as long as you are photographers but if your agency is like most, the algorithm pushes down older photos as new shoots come on line.  Basically making older shoots almost irrelevant to the search engine.

To Buffett and Lynch's maxim "buy what you know" there's the equal, but opposite, "don't buy what you know." There is no product I know better than Apple, having used some form of Apple computer for several hours a day since 1991. As an advertising writer, art director and creative director for 20 years, I've had 3 Mac Pro desktop computers and 12 to 15 MacBook Pro laptops, all of which I dove in deep as an expert in graphic design, photoshop, creating magazine and internet ads, building websites, producing and editing films on Final Cut Pro â€“ so intimate have I grown with Apple products that their massive drop in quality beginning around 2016 and growing worse until today has been more easily visible to me, than to the casual user. Before 2016 Apple products were perfect extensions of the minds of creative people like myself. Today, the MacBook Pro and the iPhone are very imperfect gadgets that have shifted my daily time from being creative, to servicing my Apple products, from repairing the banding lines across my laptop screen, to keys that don't work or that type the wrong letter, to the malfunction of one thing after another in photoshop, to the power port overheating nearly causing fires and having to buy a new $85.00 MacBook power cord every 3 months, and spending hundreds on replacing the machine's power receiver connection. I now own a toolkit of micro screwdrivers and wrenches to dismantle and self-repair my MacBooks, which I learned by being at the Mac repair shop weekly since 2016. The iPhone has a nice camera. Beyond that, the device is haunted. Suddenly a youtube video begins playing while it's in your pocket. Or suddenly music will begin playing from it without you touching it. It makes random accidental phone calls and texts, and all when it's supposed to be locked. Somehow my thigh knows the "unlock passcode." And the "tilt" function of the screen works 7 out of 10 times. And often the screen freezes and you must restart the device. My iPhone in 2015 did not do such things. But by 2019, I couldn't buy an iPhone that didn't malfunction all day, every day. The number of youtube videos on how to trouble-shoot broken or poorly designed Apple devices has skyrocketed. Something very bad has happened to quality control at Apple. Maybe they've gotten a big head and feel they don't have to try anymore? Maybe they're too big now to catch every glitch? Maybe their expectations are too high and it's just too early yet to combine a world class camera, video camera, telephone, voice recorder, music library and total all-internet device, all in your palm, without constant malfunction? Maybe the absence of Steve Jobs' thundering fist hitting tables has allowed less attention to detail within Apple? Whatever the reason, SOMETHING has certainly gone wrong at Apple. As a once super loyal, loving, even needful user of Apple, I NEVER thought I'd find myself contemplating switching to PC and Android. I'm not saying to sell Apple stock. But I personally would not buy any at the moment. Apple is at a crossroads. Once a maker of perfect products is now a behemoth with an Achilles heel: unreliability. They fix that, and they'll continue climbing to the stars. They ignore it, and they become an ancient relic of a once great past. I'm not angry. I'm saddened. I needed Apple. The old Apple. I, more than anyone, want Apple to come back to making reliable products where every function works as it's supposed to work, so we can return to being creative again, rather than developing our expertise at repairing broken devices.

That's what a value investor does....and not simply buy any companies shares at any price just because they are a good company.

Adobe is a great example of how you shouldn't dismiss a company because of large market cap. Just like Google or Amazon, Adobe is multiple businesses, all growing at a high rate. Better to think of these large tech companies like ETFs, each containing several separate excellent businesses. Like a lot of these mega-techs, Adobe even has its own VC segment, Adobe Ventures. So by owning Adobe, you can participate in the earliest stages of corporate development not available to retail investors. Apologies to Paris Hilton, but, "That's hot".

For stills, Canon have second hand 60Ds available with kit lenses or 50mm nifty fifty 1.8  lenses for around that or a bit more. 
Nikon also do the D5200, which I think has a better sensor than the Canon 60D. 
For 4k footage,  maybe look at a second hand panasonic G7 mirrorless M4/3rds. I am too a little skeptical about this but I think one important thing to consider is why are they doing this and what are the future implications if Adobe builds a useful free site. I believe that most of the images that are up for nominations are not the best sellers (since Adobe wants to keep those licenses going) and if you review your previous years statistics, most do may not make 5USD. The other important consideration is that the license options for a free image and a commercial image are different. Opting for the free site does not remove your image from being downloaded commercially if I understand it correctly. If it is true that most eligible assets receive 5USD, that is probably a better short term gain for me, BUT, I am not sure about what Adobe's longer term plan is. One final comment, one of my best sellers on Adobe I just remembered is available free on another site. People who need a more specific license for usage will need to purchase it, not get it for free.
